# ROI-boundary hardening: out-of-line enter_vsim / exit_vsim

## Context

The ROI markers `enter_vsim()` / `exit_vsim()` are `static inline` asm-volatile
blocks in `tests/fixtures/runtime/rt_c_helpers.h`. They emit `csrwi 0x7C0, 0/1`
with only a `"memory"` clobber. Because they are inline and clobber only memory,
the compiler may hoist a benchmark's vector kernel BEFORE `enter_vsim()` or sink
it AFTER `exit_vsim()` (pure register/vector compute has no memory effect, so the
"memory" clobber does not order it). For a cycle-measuring benchmark that means
kernel work can leak out of the measured window and run in QEMU (fast, MHz)
instead of vsim (cycle-accurate) -> wrong cycle count.

Today's fixtures defend per-variable with `asm volatile("" : : "vr"(x))`
force-live guards. The goal of this change is to make the BOUNDARY itself a hard
barrier so a benchmark author needs no per-variable guards.

**Decision (user): Replace.** Make `enter_vsim` / `exit_vsim` themselves
out-of-line functions. A function call is a hard barrier because the RISC-V ABI
marks GPR/FPR/vector caller-saved registers (and `vl`/`vtype`) as destroyed
across a call: the compiler must spill any live value to the stack before the
call and reload after, and it treats the opaque call conservatively, so the
kernel stays between the two calls.

**Known side effect (accepted):** with an out-of-line boundary, a V value that
crosses the boundary is spilled to the stack (shared mmap), NOT carried in a V
register. `rt_c_v_regs.c` was the ONLY fixture validating V-register-value
preservation (via its `"vr"` guards); after this change it would silently stop
testing the Phase 5 V-regfile transport. So this plan ALSO adds a hand-written
asm fixture `rt_v_regs.S` that keeps patterns in V registers across the trigger
(no compiler in the loop), restoring that coverage.

## Core architecture

```
BEFORE: rt_c_helpers.h
          static inline enter_vsim(){ asm("_hybrid_enter_pc: csrwi 0x7C0,0":::"memory"); }
        -> inlined into main(); no call boundary; kernel can drift out of [enter,exit]

AFTER:  rt_c_helpers.h
          extern void enter_vsim(void);   // declaration only
        runtime/roi_barrier.c
          __attribute__((noinline,noipa)) void enter_vsim(void){ asm("_hybrid_enter_pc: csrwi 0x7C0,0":::"memory"); }
        -> separate TU, real call; ABI caller-saved spill + opaque-call barrier
           keeps the kernel inside [enter,exit]
```

- The `_hybrid_enter_pc` / `_hybrid_exit_pc` global labels move into the
  out-of-line functions. PC-mode still resolves them by name (`tests/e2e.sh:41`
  uses `nm --defined-only ... $3=="_hybrid_enter_pc"`), which is location-blind,
  so PC mode keeps working. The label is now defined ONCE (in roi_barrier.c)
  instead of inlined per fixture -> no duplicate-symbol risk.
- The asm fixtures (`rt_all_gprs.S` etc.) define their own labels inline and do
  NOT use the header, so they are unaffected.
- gcc compiles each `.c` in the fixture link line as a separate TU (no `-flto`),
  so it cannot inline `enter_vsim` across TUs; `noinline,noipa` is belt-and-
  suspenders in case LTO is ever enabled.

