## Residual limitation (document, do not fix here)

Out-of-line markers are a strong barrier (force caller-saved spills + conservative
scheduling around an opaque call) and match the established technique for ROI
markers (e.g. gem5 `m5_work_begin`/`m5_work_end`). They are not a mathematical
guarantee against an optimizer hoisting pure, side-effect-free compute across the
call into a private spill slot; real benchmarks are anchored by memory I/O and
loop-carried dependencies, so this is not a practical concern. If a future need
demands an airtight pin, thread the carried value through the marker's
argument/return (a heavier API) - out of scope here.
